channel.title: Interleaved RSS Feed
channel.description: This is an interleaved feed of the most recent entries from each RSS source, skipping any feeds with errors.

item.title: Iran Holds Vote to Pick a President
item.description: Whoever is chosen will have to cope with a cratering economy, regional strife and deep divisions and discord at home.

item.title: 7.2-Magnitude Earthquake Strikes Off Peru, Injures 3
item.description: A tsunami alert was lifted about an hour after the quake struck off the coast of the southern region of Arequipa.

item.title: Nvidia’s Jensen Huang plays down competition worries as key supplier disappoints with subdued expectations for AI chip sales
item.description: Hype for AI is so feverish that even meeting expectations isn't enough for investors.

item.title: Brittany Was Once Barren Ground for France’s Far Right. No More.
item.description: The region along the northwest coast has few immigrants and little crime or unemployment, but the far right National Rally has made inroads saying that all three are coming.

item.title: U.S. Allies Watch the Debate With Shaking Heads and a Question: What Now?
item.description: Across Asia, there was little talk about winning, and more concern about American stability — both domestically and on crucial foreign policy issues.

item.title: China’s AI companies are reportedly rationing the use of their services because they don’t have enough chips
item.description: Blame the U.S. and its export controls blocking AI chip sales to China.

item.title: Key Debate Moments: A Night of Stumbles and Falsehoods, and More
item.description: Plus, Bronny James joins his dad at the Lakers.

item.title: Iran Holds Vote to Pick a President
item.description: Whoever is chosen will have to cope with a cratering economy, regional strife and deep divisions and discord at home.

item.title: Democrats have begun to talk about replacing Biden for the 2024 election. Here’s how that would work—and the hurdles to it happening
item.description: With Biden having already secured a presumptive nomination, Democrats’ prospects for a course change are diminishing.

item.title: Biden Administration Denies Mining and Drilling Access to Alaskan Wilderness
item.description: The Interior Department rejected a proposed industrial road through pristine land in Alaska that was needed to reach an estimated $7.5 billion copper deposit.

item.title: Brittany Was Once Barren Ground for France’s Far Right. No More.
item.description: The region along the northwest coast has few immigrants and little crime or unemployment, but the far right National Rally has made inroads saying that all three are coming.

item.title: Amid election nerves French traders race to secure funding as they foresee the worst blow to bonds
item.description: “There is nothing to win in this market.”

item.title: Supreme Court’s Abortion Rulings May Set the Stage for More Restrictions
item.description: The court’s strategy of avoidance and delay cannot last and may have been shaped by a desire to avoid controversy in an election year.

item.title: Middle East Crisis: Critically Ill Children Allowed to Leave Gaza for First Time Since May
item.description: Sixty-eight people, including sick and injured patients and their escorts, crossed the border to get treatment, the Israeli military said. The evacuation was carried out in coordination with the U.S., Egypt and the international community.

item.title: CEO of cosmetics giant L’Oreal announces slower growth as Chinese market flatlines
item.description: China had long been a growth engine for L’Oreal, with consumers snapping up its high-end cosmetics offerings.
